{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94818c49-fbf7-444b-a04b-671beb0bffd4","content":"Analyzing crash dumps is outside what I can automate here, but here's how to investigate your `.dmp` file:\n\n### Using `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- **`clrstack`** — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- **`pe` (PrintException)** — show the last exception\n- **`dumpheap -stat`** — heap summary (useful for OOM crashes)\n- **`threads`** — list all managed threads\n- **`setthread <id>` + `clrstack`** — inspect other threads\n\n### Using WinDbg (Windows)\nLoad the dump, then:\n```\n.loadby sos coreclr\n!pe            // print exception\n!clrstack      // managed stack trace\n!threads       // all threads\n```\n\n### Quick triage flow\n1. Run `pe` first — if there's an unhandled exception, this gives you the type, message, and stack trace immediately.\n2. If no exception, check `clrstack` on the faulting thread for a stack overflow or access violation.\n3. For OOM, use `dumpheap -stat` to find what's consuming memory.\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools in your environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"209a71c0-113b-4482-8ec5-0d7d5484051c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for **collecting** crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":450},"id":"6fb7df17-520f-4e17-a869-7105131b220e","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:01:05.539Z","parentId":"315fd4f2-fd4f-4c24-ba42-b5d924bc1df6"}
